## Program.cs — stdio transport with DI

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: route logs to stderr so stdout stays clean for JSON-RPC
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient("api", client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

## ApiTools.cs — tool class wrapping a REST API

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Net.Http.Json;
using System.Text.Json;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(IHttpClientFactory httpFactory, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a post by its numeric ID.")]
    public async Task<string> GetPost(
        [Description("The post ID (1-100)")] int id,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching post {Id}", id);
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("api");
        var post = await client.GetFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>(
            $"/posts/{id}", cancellationToken);
        return post.ToString();
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("List posts, optionally filtered by user ID.")]
    public async Task<string> ListPosts(
        [Description("Filter by user ID (optional)")] int? userId = null,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("api");
        var path = userId.HasValue ? $"/posts?userId={userId}" : "/posts";
        var posts = await client.GetFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>(
            path, cancellationToken);
        return posts.ToString();
    }
}
```

## How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK resolves dependencies **two ways**:

| Style | How it works |
|---|---|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | The class is instantiated per-call. Services like `IHttpClientFactory`, `ILogger<T>` are injected via the primary constructor. Register them normally in `builder.Services`. |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services can appear as method parameters directly. The SDK detects registered types and injects them — they're **excluded** from the tool's JSON schema so the LLM never sees them. |

**What the LLM sees vs. what's injected:**
- `[Description(...)]` parameters → exposed in the tool schema (LLM provides these)
- `CancellationToken`, `IProgress<T>`, `IMcpServer`, and any DI-registered service → auto-injected, invisible to the LLM

In the example above, `IHttpClientFactory` and `ILogger<ApiTools>` come from DI via the constructor. Only `id` and `userId` appear in the tool schema that the LLM interacts with.
